aa(lp51
VNow, I know it's a widespread assumption in the West
p52
aVthat as countries modernize,
p53
aVthey also westernize.
p54
aVThis is an illusion.
p55
aVIt's an assumption that modernity
p56
aVis a product simply of competition, markets and technology.
p57
aVIt is not. It is also shaped equally
p58
aVby history and culture.
p59
aVChina is not like the West,
p60
aVand it will not become like the West.
p61
aVIt will remain in very fundamental respects
p62
aVvery different.
p63
aVNow the big question here is obviously,
p64
aVhow do we make sense of China?
p65
aVHow do we try to understand what China is?
p66
aVAnd the problem we have in the West at the moment, by and large,
p67
aVis that the conventional approach
p68
aVis that we understand it really in Western terms,
p69
aVusing Western ideas.
p70
aVWe can't.
p71
aVNow I want to offer you
p72
aVthree building blocks
p73
aVfor trying to understand what China is like,
p74
aVjust as a beginning.
p75
aa(lp76
VThe first is this:
p77
aVthat China is not really a nation-state.
p78
aVOkay, it's called itself a nation-state
p79
aVfor the last hundred years,
p80
aVbut everyone who knows anything about China
p81
aVknows it's a lot older than this.
p82
aVThis was what China looked like with the victory of the Qin Dynasty
p83
aVin 221 B.C. at the end of the warring-state period \u2014
p84
aVthe birth of modern China.
p85
aVAnd you can see it against the boundaries of modern China.
p86
aVOr immediately afterward, the Han Dynasty,
p87
aVstill 2,000 years ago.
p88
aVAnd you can see already it occupies
p89
aVmost of what we now know as Eastern China,
p90
aVwhich is where the vast majority of Chinese lived then
p91
aVand live now.
p92
aa(lp93
VNow what is extraordinary about this
p94
aVis, what gives China its sense of being China,
p95
aVwhat gives the Chinese
p96
aVthe sense of what it is to be Chinese,
p97
aVcomes not from the last hundred years,
p98
aVnot from the nation-state period,
p99
aVwhich is what happened in the West,
p100
aVbut from the period, if you like,
p101
aVof the civilization-state.
p102
aVI'm thinking here, for example,
p103
aVof customs like ancestral worship,
p104
aVof a very distinctive notion of the state,
p105
aVlikewise, a very distinctive notion of the family,
p106
aVsocial relationships like guanxi,
p107
aVConfucian values and so on.
p108
aVThese are all things that come
p109
aVfrom the period of the civilization-state.
p110
aVIn other words, China, unlike the Western states and most countries in the world,
p111
aVis shaped by its sense of civilization,
p112
aVits existence as a civilization-state,
p113
aVrather than as a nation-state.
p114
aVAnd there's one other thing to add to this, and that is this:
p115
aVOf course we know China's big, huge,
p116
aVdemographically and geographically,
p117
aVwith a population of 1.3 billion people.
p118
aVWhat we often aren't really aware of
p119
aVis the fact
p120
aVthat China is extremely diverse
p121
aVand very pluralistic,
p122
aVand in many ways very decentralized.
p123
aVYou can't run a place on this scale simply from Beijing,
p124
aVeven though we think this to be the case.
p125
aVIt's never been the case.
p126
aa(lp127
VSo this is China, a civilization-state,
p128
aVrather than a nation-state.
p129
aVAnd what does it mean?
p130
aVWell, I think it has all sorts of profound implications.
p131
aVI'll give you two quick ones.
p132
aVThe first is that
p133
aVthe most important political value for the Chinese
p134
aVis unity,
p135
aVis the maintenance
p136
aVof Chinese civilization.
p137
aVYou know, 2,000 years ago, Europe:
p138
aVbreakdown \u2014 the fragmentation of the Holy Roman Empire.
p139
aVIt divided, and it's remained divided ever since.
p140
aVChina, over the same time period,
p141
aVwent in exactly the opposite direction,
p142
aVvery painfully holding this huge civilization,
p143
aVcivilization-state, together.
p144
aa(lp145
VThe second
p146
aVis maybe more prosaic,
p147
aVwhich is Hong Kong.
p148
aVDo you remember the handover of Hong Kong
p149
aVby Britain to China in 1997?
p150
aVYou may remember
p151
aVwhat the Chinese constitutional proposition was.
p152
aVOne country, two systems.
p153
aVAnd I'll lay a wager
p154
aVthat barely anyone in the West believed them.
p155
aV"Window dressing.
p156
aVWhen China gets its hands on Hong Kong,
p157
aVthat won't be the case."
p158
aVThirteen years on,
p159
aVthe political and legal system in Hong Kong
p160
aVis as different now as it was in 1997.
p161
aVWe were wrong. Why were we wrong?
p162
aVWe were wrong because we thought, naturally enough,
p163
aVin nation-state ways.
p164
aVThink of German unification, 1990.
p165
aVWhat happened?
p166
aVWell, basically the East was swallowed by the West.
p167
aVOne nation, one system.
p168
aVThat is the nation-state mentality.
p169
aVBut you can't run a country like China,
p170
aVa civilization-state,
p171
aVon the basis of one civilization, one system.
p172
aVIt doesn't work.
p173
aVSo actually the response of China
p174
aVto the question of Hong Kong \u2014
p175
aVas it will be to the question of Taiwan \u2014
p176
aVwas a natural response:
p177
aVone civilization, many systems.
p178
aa(lp179
VLet me offer you another building block
p180
aVto try and understand China \u2014
p181
aVmaybe not sort of a comfortable one.
p182
aVThe Chinese have a very, very different
p183
aVconception of race
p184
aVto most other countries.
p185
aVDo you know,
p186
aVof the 1.3 billion Chinese,
p187
aVover 90 percent of them
p188
aVthink they belong to the same race,
p189
aVthe Han?
p190
aVNow, this is completely different
p191
aVfrom the world's [other] most populous countries.
p192
aVIndia, the United States,
p193
aVIndonesia, Brazil \u2014
p194
aVall of them are multiracial.
p195
aVThe Chinese don't feel like that.
p196
aVChina is only multiracial
p197
aVreally at the margins.
p198
aVSo the question is, why?
p199
aVWell the reason, I think, essentially
p200
aVis, again, back to the civilization-state.
p201
aVA history of at least 2,000 years,
p202
aVa history of conquest, occupation,
p203
aVabsorption, assimilation and so on,
p204
aVled to the process by which,
p205
aVover time, this notion of the Han emerged \u2014
p206
aVof course, nurtured
p207
aVby a growing and very powerful sense
p208
aVof cultural identity.
p209
aa(lp210
VNow the great advantage of this historical experience
p211
aVhas been that, without the Han,
p212
aVChina could never have held together.
p213
aVThe Han identity has been the cement
p214
aVwhich has held this country together.
p215
aVThe great disadvantage of it
p216
aVis that the Han have a very weak conception
p217
aVof cultural difference.
p218
aVThey really believe
p219
aVin their own superiority,
p220
aVand they are disrespectful
p221
aVof those who are not.
p222
aVHence their attitude, for example,
p223
aVto the Uyghurs and to the Tibetans.
p224
aa(lp225
VOr let me give you my third building block,
p226
aVthe Chinese state.
p227
aVNow the relationship
p228
aVbetween the state and society in China
p229
aVis very different from that in the West.
p230
aVNow we in the West
p231
aVoverwhelmingly seem to think \u2014 in these days at least \u2014
p232
aVthat the authority and legitimacy of the state
p233
aVis a function of democracy.
p234
aVThe problem with this proposition
p235
aVis that the Chinese state
p236
aVenjoys more legitimacy
p237
aVand more authority
p238
aVamongst the Chinese
p239
aVthan is true
p240
aVwith any Western state.
p241
aVAnd the reason for this
p242
aVis because \u2014
p243
aVwell, there are two reasons, I think.
p244
aVAnd it's obviously got nothing to do with democracy,
p245
aVbecause in our terms the Chinese certainly don't have a democracy.
p246
aVAnd the reason for this is,
p247
aVfirstly, because the state in China
p248
aVis given a very special \u2014
p249
aVit enjoys a very special significance
p250
aVas the representative,
p251
aVthe embodiment and the guardian
p252
aVof Chinese civilization,
p253
aVof the civilization-state.
p254
aVThis is as close as China gets
p255
aVto a kind of spiritual role.
p256
aa(lp257
VAnd the second reason is because,
p258
aVwhereas in Europe
p259
aVand North America,
p260
aVthe state's power is continuously challenged \u2014
p261
aVI mean in the European tradition,
p262
aVhistorically against the church,
p263
aVagainst other sectors of the aristocracy,
p264
aVagainst merchants and so on \u2014
p265
aVfor 1,000 years,
p266
aVthe power of the Chinese state
p267
aVhas not been challenged.
p268
aVIt's had no serious rivals.
p269
aVSo you can see
p270
aVthat the way in which power has been constructed in China
p271
aVis very different from our experience
p272
aVin Western history.
p273
aVThe result, by the way,
p274
aVis that the Chinese have a very different view of the state.
p275
aVWhereas we tend to view it as an intruder,
p276
aVa stranger,
p277
aVcertainly an organ
p278
aVwhose powers need to be limited
p279
aVor defined and constrained,
p280
aVthe Chinese don't see the state like that at all.
p281
aVThe Chinese view the state
p282
aVas an intimate \u2014 not just as an intimate actually,
p283
aVas a member of the family \u2014
p284
aVnot just in fact as a member of the family,
p285
aVbut as the head of the family,
p286
aVthe patriarch of the family.
p287
aVThis is the Chinese view of the state \u2014
p288
aVvery, very different to ours.
p289
aVIt's embedded in society in a different kind of way
p290
aVto what is the case
p291
aVin the West.
p292
aa(lp293
VAnd I would suggest to you that actually what we are dealing with here,
p294
aVin the Chinese context,
p295
aVis a new kind of paradigm,
p296
aVwhich is different from anything
p297
aVwe've had to think about in the past.
p298
